<TEXT>
wall street is still waiting for assurance that 
the ual corps 438 billion buyout will go through but the 
companys employees say theyre willing to accept the tough 
concessions that are part of the deal 
the unions making the purchase have neither financing 
commitments nor a new management team and some investors and 
analysts say they wont take the new deal seriously until those 
issues are nailed down 
the question is who is going to manage this thing and take it 
to the banks said analyst jack hunter of howe barnes investments 
inc in chicago 
hunter said he believed the deal ultimately would go through 
but another airlines analyst who spoke on condition of anonymity 
said the deals chances were 5050 at best 
directors of ual the parent of united airlines announced an 
agreement in principle friday to sell the nations secondlargest 
carrier to its 71000 employees for cash and securities equal to 
201 a share which would create the countrys largest workerowned 
company 
the stock market reflected investor skepticism the deal will be 
done after a strong opening ual closed 2 lower at 16350 on the 
new york stock exchange 
the possibility the unions will dump ual chairman and chief 
executive stephen wolf was seen by some observers as the biggest 
threat to a successful conclusion of the deal 
wolf is perceived as a capable airline manager despite his 
abrasive relations with the unions 
frederick dubinsky chairman of the united chapter of the air 
line pilots association told a news conference in new york that 
wolf would be replaced 
its our intention to put together a topnotch senior 
management team and that will include a new ceo he said 
but later in the day union group spokesman hank krakowski said 
the group had made no such decision 
our position is were not including or precluding anyone from 
any management team at this point krakowski said 
the union group includes uniteds pilots machinists and flight 
attendants unions which together represent about twothirds of 
uals employees 
ual will spin off to shareholders its entire 50 percent stake in 
covia which is coowned by a consortium of five other airlines and 
operates an automated reservations system called apollo 
the agreement calls for employees to give up 2 billion in 
concessions over five years 
the unions would sign fiveyear contracts with nostrike 
clauses other concessions include wage cuts of up to 769 percent 
for flight attendants and machinists and up to 11 percent for 
pilots 
uals 25700 nonunion employees will negotiate their work 
conditions with the union group said their lawyer stephen fraidin 
under the agreement the pilots would own 379 percent of ual 
machinists would own 357 percent nonunion employees about 143 
percent and flight attendants about 12 percent the unions said 
the largest employeeowned company currently is publix inc a 
supermarket chain based in lakeland fla with 50000 employees 
said corey rosen executive director of the national center for 
employee ownership in oakland calif 
some ual corp employees said they were prepared to accept the 
concessions that go along with the agreement 
frederick dubinsky head of uniteds pilot union referred to 
the concessions as sweat equity and said there is no other 
decent alternative 
i would be willing to give up money myself said donna a 
flight attendant interviewed at ohare international airport who 
would not give her full name ten percent would be too much 5 
percent would hurt but i would be willing to take it 
we would never say no to job concessions said another 
flight attendant from denver but you have to look at the whole 
benefits package not just wages she said 
a 25year united pilot from washington dc said wage cuts 
should not go beyond about 10 percent but added paywise we 
will do everything we can to save the airline 
</TEXT>
