<TEXT>
three leaders of the crow indian tribe 
were convicted of fraudulently convincing two banks to approve 
loans that one of the leaders has not repaid a fourth defendant 
was acquitted 
a us district court jury friday convicted tribal chairman 
richard real bird theodore hogan and willie stewart jr on charges 
of conspiracy bank fraud and lying on a loan application robert 
s howe was acquitted of the same charges 
us district judge david ezra let the three tribal leaders 
remain free on bond until sentencing july 17 each faces up to 12 
years in prison and fines up to 25000 
the charges were part of a grand jury indictment that named 26 
tribal leaders on a total of 37 counts thirteen more trials 
about half of which probably will include real bird are scheduled 
throughout the summer 
assistant us attorney carl rostad had charged that the 
defendants misled the little horn state bank in hardin and first 
citizens bank in billings into approving loans in 1986 for hogan 
who was deeply in debt 
rostad said the defendants told the banks the tribe would pay 
hogan 296500 for land they knew already had been foreclosed on 
the banks have not been paid rostad said and hogans land 
which is near the custer battlefield national monument in 
southeastern montana eventually was sold to a nontribal member 
real bird testified that the bureau of indian affiars is holding 
38 million in coal taxes for the tribe he said the defendants 
acting on the approval of a bia employee believed that money would 
be available to pay hogan who then could repay the loans 
weve said the defendants wrongs were not affected by 
whatever the bia did or didnt do rostad said apparently the 
jury thought so as well 
but real birds lawyer rodney shepherd said this as much of 
a travesty as when the white man took everything from these people 
except their pride 
now i guess theyre trying to take that too 
</TEXT>
