<TEXT>
commissioner fred t goldberg jr says the 
internal revenue service is firmly committed to safeguarding 
taxpayers rights but critics say the word has not filtered down 
to some agents in the field 
david keating executive vice president of the national 
taxpayers union told a senate finance subcommittee friday that the 
situation could get worse as budget shortages increase pressure on 
the irs to boost collections 
as marching orders filter through the bureaucracy each 
management layer tends to rewrite the orders stronger to ensure 
that the field troops fully understand the new mission keating 
said 
the result may well be that irs employees could take a much 
tougher stand with taxpayers causing more violations of the 
taxpayer bill of rights 
goldberg testifying at a hearing on how the taxpayer protection 
law is being implemented acknowledged that his agencys 120000 
employees make mistakes but overall he said the new law is 
working we are indeed making a great deal of progress 
whether a taxpayer is due a refund owes the government taxes 
is being audited or is asking us a question that individual 
deserves to be treated fairly and with respect goldberg said 
that is the fundamental right taxpayers should expect and they 
should receive nothing less 
the taxpayer bill of rights was enacted in 1988 in response to 
complaints about the behavior of some irs employees and what 
congress viewed as a tendency to intimidate citizens 
the law for example requires the irs to spell out clearly any 
demand for taxes due prohibits the agency from rewarding employees 
on the basis of how much tax they collect and makes it more 
difficult for the irs to seize a persons property for nonpayment 
of taxes 
kay m council of high point nc told the subcommittee that 
after a long battle with the irs her husband killed himself so she 
could use his 250000 insurance policy to continue the fight 
alex is dead because of the irss arrogance and incompetence 
she contended 
the councils problem grew out of a 70000 taxshelter 
deduction they claimed on their 1979 tax return and which the irs 
rejected after alex councils death in 1988 a federal court ruled 
that the couple owed no back taxes because the irss notice of 
deficiency had been sent four months after the statute of 
limitations had expired 
keating of the national taxpayers union said it is unlikely 
that the bill of rights would have helped the councils although 
the legislation allows a taxpayer to sue for damages if the irs 
acts recklessly or intentionally breaks a law it does not permit a 
suit for careless actions 
was the irs treatment of the council family careless and 
negligent absolutely keating said was it reckless or 
intentional it might have been but that is a very difficult 
standard to prove 
the us chamber of commerce said the new law appears to have 
had a major positive impact on the relationship between taxpayers 
and the irs 
while we get plenty of telephone calls complaining about 
compliance burdens complexity and substantive tax provisions 
telephone calls from chamber smallbusiness members facing 
immediate and unwarranted levy on seizing their house or business 
or similar serious problems have declined noticeably said david 
r burton manager of the chambers tax policy center 
sen david pryor dark chairman of the subcommittee and chief 
author of the taxpayer bill of rights said the recent complaint of 
an arkansas businessman probably sums up how most americans view 
the irs 
its not that i have a problem with paying the irs every shiny 
nickel i owe the government and its not that i begrudge them 
getting tough with me if i dont pay the businessman said 
what i resent is when they bury me in computer letters dont 
even acknowledge my explanations then grab my bank account and 
ruin my credit and only then decide they were wrong after all 
irs commissioner goldberg said much the same thing we need as 
an agency to learn to stand in the other guys shoes 
</TEXT>
