<TEXT>
president bush says he will sign an executive 
order that he earlier promised and in fact claimed to have issued 
protecting chinese students from deportation 
aides said bush will release the order probably early next 
week incorporating provisions of an informal directive he had 
issued on dealing with chinese who feared for their safety if sent 
home when their visas expired many had supported the 
nowsuppressed democracy movement 
the president said his order also will extend the deferral of 
enforced departure for chinese nationals which is currently 
scheduled to expire on june 5 of this year through jan 1 1994 
reacting to criticism that he has failed to issue the executive 
order he promised last year bush said friday i did say i was 
going to have an executive order what we had was an executive 
directive from the president that had precisely the same legal 
effect as an executive order 
the president had promised the executive order when he vetoed 
congressional legislation nov 30 that was designed to protect the 
students from deportation 
he viewed the legislation as an infringement on presidential 
powers but pledged at the time that in the face of harsh 
reprisals by the beijing government against democracy advocates no 
chinese student would be forced to go home against his or her will 
the president has since said that he issued an executive order 
but instead it was a directive and to allay any concerns 
bush said friday he will now put it in the form of an executive 
order 
we dont want to take a chance on people being mistreated 
brutalized he said in a questionandanswer session to the 
american society of newspaper editors that also focused on his 
