<TEXT>
president bush is praising japanese prime 
minister toshiki kaifu for exhibiting political courage in 
championing a major trade agreement but warning that the true test 
will come in implementation of the pact 
bush lauded kaifu for the success he achieved in the month since 
the two leaders met in california to discuss trade tensions arising 
from this countrys huge 49 billion deficit with japan 
for the first time japan has committed to removing a broad 
array of structural barriers that constrain trade and impede 
imports bush said in an appearance friday before the american 
society of newspaper editors 
but he said actual results would be what counted 
neither the japanese consumer nor the american people will be 
convinced that progress is at hand until they see concrete 
results bush said 
after four days of marathon negotiations the united states and 
japan reached agreement late thursday on a set of proposals aimed 
at correcting broadbased structural barriers to trade in both 
countries 
japan promised to take a series of steps to make it easier for 
americans and other foreigners to do business in japan us 
negotiators pledged to boost americas ability to compete 
internationally by improving the education system increasing 
savings and reducing the federal budget deficit 
but us trade specialists expressed doubts friday over how far 
the japanese will go in implementing the accord especially in 
light of strong political resistance to some of the measures in 
tokyo 
a major japanese retailers group vowed to fight a key provision 
of the pact designed to relax restrictions on establishment of 
large retail stores in the country 
clyde v prestowitz jr who was a top trade negotiator in the 
reagan administration said the latest agreement bore many 
similarities to other accords dating back to 1984 and earlier that 
had failed to open japans markets 
