states are getting poorer forcing governors 
to respond with budget cuts a freeze on new programs and calls for 
higher taxes a survey says 
twenty states have either proposed or already cut spending in 
budgets previously enacted compared with eight this time a year 
ago the study by two associations said friday 
the report blamed worsening state finances on increased spending 
for medicaid education prisons and transportation problems it 
traced in part to federal requirements or spending cutbacks 
the fiscal survey of the states is taken twice yearly by the 
national governors association and the national association of 
state budget officers 
the financial outlook for states has become so bleak the report 
said that governors are even willing to propose taxes in an 
election year 
large tax proposals are not commonly enacted in years 
corresponding with gubernatorial elections the report said 
fiscal 1991 is such a year thirtysix governors races will be 
decided in november 1990 
while 21 governors have proposed tax increases new jersey and 
new york would account for more than 50 percent of the 49 billion 
raised if the new revenues were enacted the survey found 
most governors have proposed 1991 spending increases of 5 
percent to 10 percent the report said 
this range of increases suggests that states will be 
continuing current programs but not adding new initiatives said 
gerald h miller executive director of the national association of 
state budget officers 
total state yearend balances which registered a record high of 
126 billion last year are projected to drop to 83 billion by 
the end of 1990 the survey found 
the study said the most significant personal income tax 
proposals were made in kentucky new york and oklahoma 
eight states have proposed sales tax increases with new jersey 
seeking to raise more than 1 billion by boosting the rate from 6 
percent to 7 percent and by removing some exemptions rate boosts 
also are under consideration in new mexico and oklahoma 
five states have asked for business tax increases with the 
largest hike proposed in new york 
nine states want cigarette tax increases led by floridas plan 
to raise 259 million in new revenue 
four states want higher motor fuel taxes with ohio and 
washington proposing the largest increases four states seek to 
increase taxes on alcohol 
