<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures on nepal 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the people hindus comprise 90 percent of nepals 17 million 
people 5 percent are moslem and 3 percent are buddhist nepalese 
law forbids hindus to convert to christianity foreign christians 
have occasionally been expelled after being accused of 
proselytizing while some nepalese christians have been jailed 
after being convicted of trying to convert hindus king birendra is 
accorded godlike status by many of his subjects especially in the 
impoverished countryside the literacy rate is 25 percent life 
expectancy is 52 eleven percent of all babies die before the age 
of one year 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government nepal is a monarchy with a legislature called 
the rashtriya panchayat or national assembly the king appoints 
onefifth of the assemblys members the rest are elected on a 
nonpartisan basis but political observers say the king approves 
the candidates political parties have been outlawed except for a 
brief experiment with westernstyle democracy from 1959 to 1961 
king birendra 44 who studied at eton college in england and 
harvard university ascended to the throne in 1972 upon the death 
of his father king mahendra 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the economy the per capita annual income of 150 is among the 
lowest in the world the main foreign exchange earnings come from 
tourism which includes trekking and mountain climbing and from 
export of carpets an industry dominated by tibetan refugees 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the geography nepal ranges from the semitropical terai plain 
in the south to the snowcovered himalayan mountains its 
geographic area of 56827 square miles is about the size of the 
state of wisconsin the country is wedged between asias two 
biggest powers india to the east south and west china to the 
north 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
history hindubuddhist culture was flourishing in the katmandu 
valley by the 4th century ad by medieval times many small 
principalities had emerged one of the most dominant was that of 
the gurkhas whose soldiers still serve in the armies of india and 
britain and in united nations peacekeeping forces nepal is proud 
of never having been colonized although it was a nominal british 
protectorate from 1816 to 1923 
the present shaha dynasty dates to the 17th century although 
from 1846 to 1951 real power rested with the rana family which 
installed a system of hereditary prime ministers whose descendants 
are still active in the early 1950s nepal started opening up to 
the outside world emerging from an isolation nurtured by its 
rulers and fostered by geography initially india was the major 
trading part but in the past two years nepal has sought other 
commercial ties especially with china 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

