<TEXT>
us businessmen trying to penetrate japans market 
often express frustration at the clubby nature of much of this 
countrys business and the trade reforms japan will undertake are 
meant to promote competition 
japan and the united states announced an agreement on the 
reforms thursday 
the government issued a report friday outlining its plans to 
change the deepseated business practices that contribute to the 
united states 49 billion trade deficit with japan 
it said the fair trade commission will subject the countrys 
corporate groups known as keiretsu to audits every two years 
companies within such a group own each others stock and buy 
products and services from each other excluding foreign companies 
or raising their costs 
the report said the audits will look at suppliercustomer 
transactions financing arrangements and personal ties 
the commission is to publish its findings and take steps 
including stricter enforcement of the antimonopoly act to address 
anticompetitive and exclusionary practices the report said 
in addition government powers to restrict foreign investment or 
technology imports on grounds they might adversely affect japanese 
companies will be revised the report said 
such restrictions are not needed on a general basis the 
report said 
the commission also promised to simplify procedures for 
corporate mergers and acquisitions foreigners complain that 
present rules hinder them from putting their money to work in japan 
the government said however there were sound economic reasons 
for forming corporate groups 
in the latest issue of economic eye magazine an analyst 
ryutaro komiya said the groups did not deserve the criticism they 
received 
he said that while the sales of us automaker general motors 
are more than double those of japans no 1 automaker toyota 
its employees are 13 times more numerous 
toyota contracts out much of the work that gm handles 
inhouse thus the toyota group of subcontractors is akin to gms 
internal divisions its not a question of good vs bad business 
arrangements komiya said 
he said that within a keiretsu a firm will get no sympathy 
or sales from other group members with products that are more 
expensive or of lower quality than market standards 
another point of contention between the united states and japan 
has been japans policies on retailing the government protects 
small shops by requiring large stores to obtain the consent of 
their smaller neighbors before opening the process can take 10 
years 
while refusing to abolish the law the government promised 
revisions including a shortening of this coordination processing 
period to less than 18 months if problems persist the 
government may decide in three years to exempt parts of japan from 
the law the report said 
the supermarket chain life stores co said last week it was 
suing the government for the equivalent of 63 million on grounds 
it suffered losses from not being allowed to open a new branch 
on friday toshiaki namiki a spokesman for the company said 
the promise of change would not lead the company to drop its suit 
he said its aim was to attack the law not to win compensation 
the united states has argued that the reforms would help 
japanese consumers who pay some of the worlds highest prices 
because of the complex distribution system and myriad government 
regulations 
but some consumers see advantages in the small stores consumer 
groups have said cultural aspects and community relationships 
should also be taken into consideration 
