<TEXT>
in the computer studies room 
at maghaberry prison a small clerkish man taps away at a braille 
typewriter preparing a text for the blind 
bobby bates was one of the shankill butchers a protestant 
murder squad whose throatcutting atrocities against roman 
catholics exceeded even northern irelands savage standards 
thirteen years into a life sentence for 10 murders with a 
history of violent behavior behind bars 42yearold basher 
bates comes across as a changed man he works and eats alongside 
catholic prisoners he has discovered christ he makes no excuses 
for his crimes 
the new bobby bates is a product of maghaberry prison which 
opened in 1986 as an alternative lockup for inmates who want to 
leave the paramilitary milieu learn a skill and one day return 
to a peaceful life outside prison 
left behind in the older maze prison outside belfast are the 
truly committed still segregating themselves into republican 
catholic and loyalist protestant cellblocks still refusing to 
work or do anything else that could be read as acknowledging that 
their offenses were criminal not political 
simply by choosing maghaberry instead of the maze a prisoner 
tacitly signals he is removing himself from the battleground and 
rehabilitation can begin 
maghaberry is part of the quiet transformation of northern 
irelands prison system in the decade since the maze seethed with 
protest and 10 inmates led by bobby sands of the irish republican 
army captured world attention by fasting to death 
the government has always seen selfimposed segregation as a 
perpetuation of the conflict between republicans fighting to rid 
northern ireland of british rule and loyalists fighting to 
maintain the union with britain 
attempts to force integration have invariably met resistance 
indeed the one jail where tension persists is belfast prison 
where about 650 pretrial inmates are demanding segregation 
several belfast guards have been beaten in recent months and 
four have been fired prosecuted or suspended since 1983 for 
mistreating prisoners a mass breakout was foiled in october 
since maghaberry opened 164 maze prisoners have gone there by 
choice now two years after it became fully operational it has 
about 275 prisoners and 520 are in the maze 
had bobby bates not moved to maghaberry he probably would have 
stayed in jail for the rest of his life as recommended by the 
judge now he may stand a chance of freedom in the next decade 
the prison service felt confident enough to invite four foreign 
journalists to visit maghaberry and the maze last month and chat in 
private with prisoners the only condition was that no prison 
officials be identified because they are targets for assassination 
i think the government is anxious to get the prisoners out as 
much as anybody else said the rev denis faul a catholic priest 
and human rights campaigner in close contact with prison 
authorities and prisoners families 
there are very many people in prison both from the protestant 
and the catholic side who would not normally be in prison for 
any type of crime other than a politically motivated crime he 
said in an interview 
nearly 2800 people have been killed in northern ireland since 
sectarian violence began in august 1969 the violence has declined 
in recent years 
the number of security offenders sentenced once forecast to 
reach 3000 is about 800 many were jailed 10 years ago or more 
and the government has been persuaded that at least some can be 
freed without risk 
wellbehaved prisoners with release dates are eligible for a 
weeks furlough at summer and christmas some prisoners 
incarcerated in britain have been moved to northern ireland to be 
nearer their families 
most prisoners on fixed sentences can expect onehalf off if 
they behave as opposed to onethird in britain 
four prisoners were learning bricklaying in a maghaberry 
workshop one an ira man serving life for killing a soldier said 
he left the maze because i didnt fancy that environment 
anymore 
he was 34 had served 14 years and expected to be released in 
1992 he went home last summer and at christmas 
i met people my age who are married with kids settled down 
he said the amount of people i didnt know it was like there 
was a gulf between myself and my family 
did he have regrets it was something you got caught up in and 
you thought it was worth it but in retrospect you wouldnt 
have done it 
working beside him was a loyalist doing life for aiding and 
abetting a murder he had a wife and four children all those 
years lost he remarked a life completely wasted 
no such sentiments are expressed at the maze a maximumsecurity 
sprawl of hshaped cellblocks 
republicans and loyalists locked in separate uprights of each 
h never meet or work they have their own gyms exercise yards 
billiard tables and libraries 
why not move to maghaberry because its saying forget your 
republicanism and become part of a criminal system an ira lifer 
said but we are not criminal prisoners we are political 
prisoners 
ira supporters argue that the journalists visit is a propaganda 
exercise that abuses do occur in belfast prison and at police 
interrogation centers 
they maintain britain has no right to be in ireland at all let 
alone to jail people who see themselves as freedom fighters 
we say northern ireland as a concept is illegal and should 
never have been set up said a maze republican on whose cell 
wall hung portraits of che guevara and jesus christ 
conversation kept moving back to 1983 when 38 prisoners escaped 
from the maze in a mass breakout and half were recaptured 
immediately one told a reporter of being beaten and set upon by 
dogs 
the prison service doesnt deny the abuses but says they 
happened in the heat of the immediate aftermath of the breakout 
and that the violence was mutual leaving one prison officer dead 
and several injured it insists abuses could not happen now 
compensation was paid to 19 prisoners who alleged being 
assaulted but no prison official was ever disciplined for the 1983 
incidents 
last month an irish court ruled against extraditing two maze 
escapees believing they might face reprisals 
faul said there had been no serious incident of brutality 
since 1983 in any of northern irelands four prisons 
by and large allowing for the difficulty of imprisoning large 
numbers of men and so on conditions have been excellent faul 
said 
he supported the irish court decision and said the british 
can only blame themselves if they had put the prison officers on 
trial or had dismissed them and could show that to the court then 
the prisoners would have been sent back 
in fauls view whatever improvements are made in the lives of 
northern irelands catholic minority are undermined by the 
nonaccountability of the security forces british army police 
prison officers for killing and illtreating persons 
this he said is one of the major problems thats keeping the 
ira in existence 
