<TEXT>
greek voters who cast their ship of state 
adrift 10 months ago are being asked for a third time to finally 
put someone at the helm 
but sundays parliamentary election like those last june and 
november could end without a clear winner and again leave greece 
with a weak coalition unable to cope with a foundering economy and 
a resurgence of terrorism 
the outcome may also have bearing on the countrys four us 
military bases which could be forced to close in november unless a 
new agreement is reached with washington 
the conservative new democracy party which missed a majority by 
about 1 percent of the vote last november believes it can win 
sunday the socialists and communists neither strong enough to win 
alone hold out the hope of forging a leftist coalition 
but after almost a year of indecision and near political 
paralysis opinion polls indicate the likely outcome is continued 
deadlock and new elections prime minister xenophon zolotas 86 a 
former governor of the bank of greece remains caretaker until a 
new government is chosen 
new democracy argues that greeks must make hard choices for hard 
times the choice is simple economic reform or economic ruin says 
71yearold party leader constantine mitsotakis who promises to 
slash public spending and restructure the economy 
this is what is at stake in these elections your wages and 
pensions the bread of your families mitsotakis told his final 
campaign rally friday night 
however his socialist and communist opponents describe his plan 
