a man was arrested saturday on murder and 
attempted murder charges accused of spiking cocacola with an 
outlawed rat poison that killed a neighbor and crippled two 
children in 1988 authorities said 
george trepal 41 was arrested without incident at his sebring 
home and charged with one count of murder six counts of attempted 
murder and several product tampering charges 
the fbi said the october 1988 poisonings of the carr family of 
alturas was the nations only known case of deliberate thallium 
poisoning 
trepal was a neighbor of the carrs when family members ingested 
the outlawed rat killer from an eightpack of 16ounce soda bottles 
at their home said lynne breidenbach a polk county sheriffs 
spokeswoman 
there was a definite motive but were not at liberty to 
discuss it because the investigation is in its infancy she said 
she added that the arrest was based on a sealed grand jury 
indictment returned thursday 
peggy carr 41 was placed on life support and died march 3 
1989 her son duane dubberly 16 and stepson travis carr 16 were 
left paralyzed by the poison 
mrs carrs husband parearlyn carr and three others also 
absorbed traces of the chemical but did not become ill carr 
contacted saturday by the associated press said he had no comment 
on the arrest 
trepal also was charged with seven counts of poisoning food or 
water and one count of tampering with a consumer product he was 
held in the polk county jail without bond 
health investigators determined within six weeks of the 
poisoning that a deliberate act of tampering was involved and ruled 
out the tampa bottling plant and the soda distribution system as 
the source of the thallium sulfate which has been banned for 
general use since 1965 
tests performed by the fbi on three unopened bottles showed the 
crimped metal caps had been removed and replaced and traces of the 
toxic pesticide were found inside 
based on the amount of thallium found in the residue in the 
empty bottles a state epidemiologist estimated each bottle 
contained about a half gram of thallium one gram is considered a 
fatal dose for humans 
thallium sulfate can be found in the form of a crystal powder or 
a paste which dissolves in water 
investigators from the fbi food and drug administration polk 
county sheriffs office and state attorneys office were involved 
in the case 
