<TEXT>
the countdown began saturday for 
space shuttle discovery and its launch of the 15 billion hubble 
space telescope the observatory astronomers hope will solve some 
basic mysteries of space and time 
countdown for tuesdays liftoff began on time at 3 pm edt an 
hour after the five astronauts arrived 
its been a long time happening and now its really here 
said discoverys commander air force col loren j shriver this 
is the end of a fairly long wait but i think in the case of 
this payload the hubble space telescope its well worth the 
wait 
were very very anxious to get it up there and get it into 
operation mission specialist bruce mccandless ii told a small 
crowd of reporters photographers and astronaut family members 
air force spokesman ken warren said forecasters expected a 90 
percent chance of favorable weather for a tuesday launch with a 10 
percent chance of strong surface winds that could delay the launch 
after arriving from johnson space center in houston the 
astronauts were driven to the launch pad to view the hubble space 
telescope which they are to deploy on the second day of the 
fiveday mission it is the most expensive unmanned spacecraft ever 
built by nasa and has endured seven years of delay because of 
technical problems and the 1986 challenger explosion 
the space agency finished charging the telescopes 
nickelhydrogen batteries saturday afternoon technicians then 
began a final sweep of the shuttles payload bay removing the 
battery chargers and any remaining protective coverings the 
payload bay doors were to be closed early sunday 
technicians also repaired a shuttle engine cable and replaced a 
damaged connector that was discovered late friday 
because the telescopes nickelhydrogen batteries must be 
recharged in a week nasa plans to halt launch attempts for eight 
days if discovery does not lift off by friday the batteries will 
power the telescope from the time it is disconnected from the 
shuttles power system during deployment until its two 
energycollecting solar panels take over in space 
nasa has up to six hours to launch discovery starting from 847 
am tuesday but the space agency limits the crews time in an 
orbiter before launch to slightly more than five hours to prevent 
fatigue so that the launch window would be shorter if a 
problem developed after the crew went into the shuttle 
it is the longest period of opportunity for launch since the 
1986 challenger mission said terry willingham nasa test director 
we want to give ourselves every opportunity to get this launch 
off in the first few days willingham said 
the telescope once deployed is to orbit 380 miles above earth 
for 15 years it will be capable of detecting objects 50 times 
fainter and with 10 times greater clarity than the best 
groundbased observatory 
astronomers expect to study stars and galaxies so distant that 
their light has been traveling to earth for 14 billion years 
in addition to shriver and mccandless the crew includes marine 
col charles f bolden jr the pilot and mission specialists 
steven a hawley and kathryn sullivan 
</TEXT>
