<TEXT>
novelist mario vargas llosa appeared to be the 
frontrunner in sundays presidential election but another 
political neophyte may force him into a runoff in this country 
plagued by rebel attacks and soaring inflation 
besieged by a savage decadelong leftist insurgency and 
impoverished by hyperinflation running at 2000 percent annually 
peruvians have grown distrustful of politicians promises of easy 
solutions 
the countrys 10 million voters are to elect a new congress and 
choose a successor to populist president alan garcia who is 
ineligible for reelection to a consecutive fiveyear term 
leftist rebels have launched numerous attacks aimed at scaring 
voters away from the polls and have threatened more action sunday 
the countrys 80000man police force and army units are on alert 
to protect voters and candidates against attacks by the maoist 
shining path guerrillas 
six candidates for congress were assassinated across peru in 
recent weeks more than 18000 people have been killed as a result 
of the 10yearold insurgency the governnment says half the 
country is under emergency rule because of the rebels 
public opinion polls indicate support for vargas llosa has been 
dropping fast in recent weeks as voters have begun to see him as 
just another politician 
vargas llosa 54 running on a freemarket platform is still 
the leading presidential contender in the field of nine candidates 
but an 11thhour surge by political newcomer alberto fujimori the 
son of japanese immigrants has dimmed vargas llosas chances for a 
firstround victory 
fujimori 51 was a political unknown as recently as a month 
ago his meteoric rise in the past two weeks has stunned political 
analysts and public opinion survey firms 
polls open at 8 am edt and close at 3 pm voting is required 
by law unofficial results are expected sunday night but official 
returns will not be available for weeks 
as late as february voter support for vargas llosa was above 50 
percent sufficient to avoid a runoff but analysts say an 
aggressive campaign by the ruling leftofcenter aprista party has 
created fear in voters about the social cost of the severe 
austerity measures vargas llosa proposes 
vargas llosa despite being a political independent also has 
been tainted by the support he has received in his twoyear 
campaign from traditional politicians discredited in past 
governments pollsters say 
surveys made as recently as a week ago show vargas llosa falling 
to around 35 percent of voter support fujimori an agricultural 
engineer running on an independent ticket has leaped into second 
place with 24 percent of voter preference 
if vargas llosa falls short of a majority he will be forced 
into a runoff most likely in early june 
and if his vote total is significantly less than 50 percent his 
centerright democratic front coalition also could fall short of 
majority control in the 60seat senate and the 180seat chamber of 
deputies 
that would make it difficult for him to impose the radical 
reforms he is seeking 
we have been observing a tendency first in lima and then in 
the provinces that is so strong that it has disconcerted 
pollsters said manuel saavedra director of the peruvian company 
for market research 
analysts say fujimoris success is a reflection of the 
alienation of peruvian voters who feel loyalty to no party and are 
looking for miraculous painless solutions to the countrys crisis 
peruvians are in search of a savior said manuel torrado 
president of datum a market research firm 
in the closing days of his campaign vargas llosa responded to 
the attacks against him by his opponents the heaviest criticism 
came from the aprista partys candidate luis alva castro 48 who 
was favored to win a runoff spot against the novelist until 
fujimoris lastminute surge 
in his last television appearance friday night before a midnight 
ban on campaigning the novelist accused the garcia government of 
using all its resources to deceive humble people about what i 
desire for peru 
they say for example that i defend the rich and that if i 
reach the presidency i will forget the poor that is not true my 
fellow countrymen i dont owe anything to the rich of this 
country 
i have left literature and entered politics because i believe 
that through freedom this country can be changed so that people 
are assured work and food 
vargas llosa is seeking a strong mandate from the electorate to 
put into practice an economic shock program his program includes 
removal of price controls reduction in import restrictions sale 
of moneylosing state enterprises and elimination of tens of 
thousands of jobs from the bloated bureaucracy 
vargas llosa bestknown as the author of aunt julia and the 
scriptwriter among other novels entered the political arena in 
1987 after organizing a huge demonstration against garcias plan to 
nationalize the banks 
