<TEXT>
to a small band of mohawk indians living in 
the forest around miner lake their territory is a sovereign nation 
totally independent of the united states and new york state 
the mohawks at miner lake are at a standoff with state troopers 
who have had them surrounded since march 30 when a vermont 
national guard helicopter on a medical emergency mission was forced 
down after it was struck by gunfire that caused minor wounds to a 
doctor on board 
troopers have vowed to investigate the shots they think came 
from the indian land the mohawks say theyll die for their 
sovereignty they have investigated they say and turned up 
nothing 
continuing negotiations have gone nowhere offers made by the 
indians to allow police on the land have been rejected so far by 
the state as too narrow and limiting for their investigation 
things are pretty much the same as they have been state 
police lt donald romanchuk said saturday 
the mohawks are righteous viewing their community as perhaps 
the last frontier for the traditional mohawk way of life 
isolated behind barricades though resourceful mohawks have 
sometimes resorted to the 1990 method of getting their message out 
by fax machine 
the mohawk people have never relinquished their land they 
have never given up being a people as independent as possible 
said their spokesman darryl martin in order to survive and not 
be assimilated into western culture we keep this law alive today 
those in the community known as ganienkeh do not care what 
judges governors or state troopers in the united states say about 
the complicated issue of indian tribal sovereignty 
sovereignty is not something somebody can give you said 
martin sovereignty comes from the people we are not waiting for 
some commission somewhere to decide whether we are sovereign we 
are sovereign 
we respect the laws of the united states when we travel on 
that land as guests our laws apply here 
new york officials cite acts of congress giving them criminal 
jurisdiction over the indian lands as justification for their 
investigation of the helicopter shooting the indians cite 
treaties the state also has sued the indians to try to close a 
bingo hall that opened in 1988 
a lawyer representing the indians dennis curtin called the 
ganienkeh residents fundamentalist mohawks 
theyre trying to preserve their culture their language 
their heritage their environment he said 
when you look at the rest of society theirs is one to be 
looked up to said curtin who insists that fears of bloodshed at 
ganienkeh are legitimate absolutely every one of them is willing 
to die for sovereignty 
the ganienkeh mohawks first set up their traditional settlement 
by takig over state land around moss lake 150 miles to the 
southwest in 1974 the moss lake occupation erupted into violence 
the same year when gunfire from the encampment wounded a man and a 
9yearold girl passing by in separate cars the mohawks said they 
had been fired upon first 
in a response similar to the present situation outside miner 
lake state troopers set up roadblocks around moss lake in an armed 
standoff that lasted more than three years no arrests were ever 
made in connection with the shootings 
it was at moss lake that gov mario cuomo learned firsthand how 
important sovereignty is to these mohawks then new yorks 
secretary of state cuomo negotiated an end to the tense situation 
by persuading the mohawks to move to their present community near 
the canadian border 
its a complicated thing because the indians regard themselves 
as a sovereignty cuomo said they had never dealt with 
anything under a sovereignty they are a nation and they will deal 
only with a nation 
cuomo finally gained credibility with the mohawk negotiators by 
persuading the fbi to deputize a state police official qualifying 
him as a federal representative in the eyes of the traditionalist 
mohawks 
it took us weeks and weeks to figure that simple thing out 
but it is very important to the indians because it involves their 
understanding of themselves said cuomo they see themselves as 
a nation 
fifty miles to the west at the st regis akwasasne reservation 
the pros and cons of sovereignty has divided the 4000 mohawks who 
live there 
seth shapiro the lawyer defending kakwirakeron in a federal 
court trial on charges he led armed defiance of a state police raid 
on casinos at the st regis mohawk reservation tried 
unsuccessfully to apply the helsinki accord to the indians 
there is an absolute parallel to what is going on with 
lithuania and the soviet union shapiro said we believe in 
sovereignty with lithuania for all these other places we say 
sovereignty is important but not when it comes to our native 
americans they just want to be left alone 
