<TEXT>
since last fall the price of cocoa has risen 300 a ton off the 
14year low of 900 despite six consecutive seasons of surplus 
production and record inventories 
analysts say there are several reasons for the upsurge 
including a concern the west african crop areas primarily the 
ivory coast nigeria and cameroon have received only a quarter of 
their normal rainfall in the past two months 
there also has been some warming of the central pacific ocean 
off the coasts of chile and peru a phenomenon that in the past has 
caused dry spells and droughts in the cocoa growing areas of brazil 
and in west africa 
political unrest in the ivory coast the worlds largest cocoa 
producer also is providing a boost to prices 
the cocoa market has been further boosted by a concern over the 
availabilty of cocoa to processors says sandra kaul an analyst 
with shearson lehman hutton inc in new york 
ms kaul noted the activity in the market is taking place in 
between two crops the main crop harvest takes place between 
september and january and supplies have been sold out the 
secondary harvest begins next month 
because so little cocoa is available producers have been less 
inclined to protect themselves in the futures market where they 
could sell cocoa contracts and lock in prices now 
ms kaul added that against the background of concern about the 
weather and political stability the international cocoa agreement 
has been extended for another two years eliminating the prospect 
that the agreements 250000 ton buffer stock of cocoa beans will 
be released into the market 
judy ganes an analyst with merrill lynch in new york said the 
bullish cocoa market was somewhat of a surprise because most 
traders had a bearish expectation of a soft market after years of 
oversupply 
one analyst who asked not to be identified said the technical 
nature of the price rise is an indication traders are finding a way 
to construe any bit of information about the crop as bullish 
certainly if it rains in west africa or any of the other 
cocoa growing regions its the price surge over ms ganes 
said 
</TEXT>
