<TEXT>
oil prices are weakening a decline traced to 
rising opec production seasonal slack demand and the notable 
absence of any jolting events such as the exxon valdez spill that 
helped traumatize the market last year 
nonetheless it appears unlikely that prices will fall 
dramatically and some analysts say the market is much more stable 
than at any time in the recent past if these trends persist 
motorists shouldnt see any sudden price changes in gasoline as the 
summer driving season begins 
others however contend that the oil market in general is much 
more vulnerable to disruptions now partly because of the growing 
integration of the world economy and some politically unstable 
hotspots 
if for example soviet oilworkers went on strike or chemical 
warfare broke out in the middle east or another major spill fouled 
the us coast the psychological impact could give the oil market 
a serious case of nerves and force prices up sharply 
most of the oilprice decline this past week was attributed to 
new evidence that suggests the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries is aggressively producing oil in what has been a slack 
demand period between winter and summer when most refiners 
curtail operations 
opec accounts for a growing chunk of world production and has 
doubled its market share in the united states over the past four 
years from about 12 percent to nearly 25 percent 
the price of west texas intermediate the primary grade of us 
crude and a widely followed market barometer finished the past 
week at 1915 per 42gallon barrel down more than 1 a barrel 
from a week earlier and down about 4 from the beginning of this 
year wholesale gasoline prices also dropped sharply but some 
strategists believe these declines wont last long 
right now its perceived there isnt going to be a crash in 
prices said kevin lindemer associate director of cambridge 
energy research associates in cambridge mass we can expect a 
little bit of price weakness but i think this is something thats 
typical for this time of the year 
it remains unclear why opec production is so intense oil 
intelligence references that track the cartels output estimate the 
13 members are producing about 235 million barrels a day which is 
about the highest level in eight years if that persists a serious 
price decline would seem inevitable 
at the same time however much of that oil is getting soaked up 
by industrialized areas of the world moreover potential markets 
that nobody thought existed a year ago the most notable example 
is eastern europe could provide new sources of demand for opec 
oil 
edward n krapels president of energy security analysis a 
washingtonbased research concern that tracks prices worldwide 
said theres another wrinkle in the world oil equation the 
difference between lowsulphur sweet crudes such as west texas 
intermediate and the highersulphur sour grades that span much 
of what opec sells 
the sour crudes are plentiful but require intense refining to 
produce highquality gasoline while sweet crudes are much cheaper 
to process this is important because us oil companies play a 
major role in refining sour crudes and could use their leverage to 
hold down prices charged by producers 
we think west texas intermediate will stabilize at about 19 
to 20 a barrel but unfortunately for exporters highsulphur oil 
will fall further krapels said predicting less than 15 a 
barrel for dubai a standard middle east crude 
so its kind of a bifurcated view he said you expect the 
price of the dirty stuff to be lower than the clean stuff the 
refiners are in a very strong negotiating position 
in other business and economic news this past week 
the governmentdirected savings amp loan salvation effort took 
several dramatic turns most notable were the record 30year prison 
sentence imposed on a failed texas thrifts former executive 
convicted of fraud a congressional auditor prediction that the 
bailout cost could hit 500 billion if the economy falters more 
than triple the amount the white house forecast last year and 
senate approval of labor lawyer timothy ryan as top sampl regulator 
nullifying a court decision that had threatened to derail the 
entire rescue effort 
japan and the united states agreed on a broad economic pact 
designed to make it easier for foreigners to do business in japan 
and make american industry more competitive the pact was hailed as 
a major event in relations between the worlds two largest 
economies but it remains unclear whether and when its effects will 
be felt 
the long battle for control of united airlines appeared to be 
near an end directors of parent company ual corp agreed to a 
438 billion takeover offer from employees about 24 billion 
less than a debtfinanced acquisition proposal that collapsed a 
half year ago 
general motors corp named robert stempel as chairman and chief 
executive to succeed roger smith when he retires in august the 
appointment of stempel to take the helm of the nations biggest 
industrial company was expected and many believe he will play a 
more aggressive role in gms car design and development than smith 
who was widely criticized because of his accounting background 
</TEXT>
